== PREVENTION DURING BIRTH

What happens during labor and delivery has the biggest impact on tearing. Here's what the evidence supports:

=== Warm Compresses

Applying warm compresses to your perineum during pushing is one of the most effective prevention techniques:

- Reduces the rate of severe tears
- Helps the tissue become more flexible
- Feels soothing during an intense time
- No risks or downsides

_Ask your provider or nurse to apply warm compresses during the pushing stage._ This is a simple request that can make a real difference.

=== Slow, Controlled Crowning

How your baby's head emerges matters enormously:

- _Slow is better._ When the head crowns slowly, your tissue has time to stretch.
- _Breathing through crowning._ Instead of forceful pushing when the head is emerging, small breaths or "panting" gives tissue more time.
- _Hands-on support._ Your provider can apply gentle counter-pressure to help control the speed.

_What to ask your provider:_
- "Can you help me slow down when the baby is crowning?"
- "Will you guide me on when to push and when to breathe?"
- "Can we take extra time during crowning if possible?"

=== Positions That Reduce Tearing

Your birth position affects perineal stretching. Positions that tend to be gentler:

_Side-lying_
- Takes pressure off the perineum
- Allows for slow, controlled delivery
- One of the gentlest positions for your tissue

_Hands and knees_
- Opens the pelvis
- Uses gravity differently than on your back
- Allows for natural positioning of baby's head

_Semi-reclined (not flat on back)_
- Better than flat on your back
- Still allows some gravity assistance
- Common in many birth settings

_Positions that increase tearing risk:_
- Lying flat on your back with legs in stirrups
- Deep squatting (though this can be helpful for other reasons)
- Lithotomy position (flat on back, legs held up)

_Important:_ The "best" position is one where you feel comfortable and your baby is doing well. Don't sacrifice a safe delivery to avoid tearing—but if you have options, these positions are worth considering.

=== Other Helpful Techniques

_Water birth:_ Some research suggests laboring or delivering in water reduces tearing, possibly because warm water relaxes the perineum.

_Avoid directed pushing:_ When providers count and direct pushing ("Push! Push! Push!"), it can lead to faster, more forceful delivery. Following your body's urges may result in gentler births.

_Allow time between contractions:_ During crowning, pausing between pushes lets tissue stretch gradually.

